Grants, Benefits And Compensation: An Overview
There are a number of forms of financial relief available to different people in different circumstances, including:
* The Unemployment Insurance Fund
* The Occupational Injuries and Diseases Compensation Fund
* The Road Accidents Fund
Who can claim from which fund?
Grants
There are a number of grants for poor people provided by the South African Social Security Agency.
All grants are for poor people only (a "means test" applies).
Unemployment Insurance
If you have been employed, you can get unemployment insurance benefits from the Unemployment Insurance Fund (UIF) run by the National Department of Labour.
Compensation
If you are temporarily or permanently disabled because of an accident at work, you can get compensation from the Compensation Fund at the National Department of Labour.
If you are injured in a motor vehicle accident, you can get compensation from the Road Accident Fund for your medical expenses, disablement, and loss of income.
Home > Publications > Public Information > T > Government Financial Assistance &gt Social Security Grants
Social Security Grants
The South African Social Security Agency (SASSA) has three types of grant for looking after children:
* Child Support Grant
* Care Dependency Grant
* Foster Child Grant.
You can get a child support grant for each child under 14, if you are the child's primary care-giver.
You can get a care dependency grant for each child under 18 who needs full-time care because of a physical or mental disability, if you are the child's parent or guardian.
Both of these grants depend on how poor you are.
You can get a foster child grant if you have been legally appointed a foster parent by a court.
Whether you get this grant depends on how poor the child is, NOT on how poor you are.
However, you CAN get a foster child grant and a care dependency grant, if you qualify for both.
For adults, SASSA has the following kinds of grants:
* Old age grant
* Disability grant
* War veteran's grant.
The old age grant is for women over 60 and men over 65.
The disability grant is for adults over 18 who are not able to work because of their disability.
If you were disabled because of an accident at work, you may be able to get compensation from the Occupational Injuries Compensation Fund .
If you were disabled because of a motor vehicle accident, you may be able to get compensation from the Road Accident Fund.
The war veterans grant is for adults over 60 or anyone who is unable to work because of a disability, and who served in the 1st or 2nd World War or the Korean War.
The provincial Department of Social Development can also provide temporary help in crisis situations with a financial award called "social relief of distress".
This is for people who cannot provide for their families' basic needs because of a crisis of a temporary nature.
Home > Publications > Public Information > T > Government Financial Assistance &gt Unemployment Insurance Fund (UIF) Benefits
Unemployment Insurance Fund (UIF) Benefits
If you have been employed before, then you can collect Unemployment Insurance from the Unemployment Insurance Fund (UIF) if you have been unemployed for more than 14 days.
If you have never had a job you cannot claim from the UIF.
Everyone who works for more than 24 hours per month is supposed to be registered with the UIF and to make a contribution of 1% of their earnings (along with contributions from their employer) to the UIF.
If you have been contributing, you can claim benefits if you become unemployed (if you are fired or retrenched, but not if you quit).
You must claim your UIF benefit within 6 months of becoming unemployed.
How much you can claim and for how long you can claim depend on how long you were working and how much you were earning.
You can get one day's benefit for every 6 days you worked, up to a maximum of 238 days (which you reach after working for 4 years).
You cannot claim any benefit for any amount of time that you worked and at the same time received a Social Services grant for yourself.
If you earned more than R8099 per month before, you will get a flat benefit of R101,18 per day.
For example, if you earned R1000 per month before, you will get R17,34 per day.
UIF can also be claimed by the partner or dependants of a worker who has died.
You can also get a UIF benefit if you can't work because of ill-health (for up to 6 months, but takes into account any sick leave).
You can get a maternity benefit when you have a child, or an adoption benefit if you adopt a child younger than two years and have to take off work to look after the child.
Only one parent can get maternity or adoption benefits.
You must apply for the maternity benefit at least eight weeks before the birth of the child.
You must apply for the adoption benefit within 6 months of the adoption order.
You can apply for UIF benefits at any Labour Centre
Home > Publications > Public Information > T > Government Financial Assistance &gt Occupational Injuries Compensation Fund (formerly Workers' Compensation)
Occupational Injuries Compensation Fund (formerly Workers' Compensation)
The accident must be identified by its date, time and place and must have happened as a direct result of your employment.
For temporary total disablement, you can get compensation equal to 75% of your monthly earnings, up to a maximum of R2 868,00 per week.
For permanent disablement, where the degree of disablement is 30% or less, you can get a lump sum (one payment) which is usually equal to 15 times your monthly earnings.
However, the minimum lump sum is 15 times R1359,00 = R20 385,00 (if you earn less than R1359 you will get R20 385).
The maximum lump sum 15 times R6 963,00 = R104 445,00 (if you earn more than R6963,00 you will get R104 445,00).
If the degree of permanent disablement is 31% or more, you will not get a lump sum, you will get a monthly pension instead.
The pension for total permanent disablement (degree of disablement 100%) is equal to 75% of your monthly earnings.
If the degree of disablement is less than 100%, the pension is proportionately less.
If the employee's earnings are R1 359,00 per month or less, the pension is calculated on R1 359,00.
The minimum pension in respect of 100% permanent disablement is therefore R1 019,25 per month.
Where an employee dies, the surviving spouse is entitled to
* a lump sum equal to two times the monthly pension to which the employee would have been entitled to if 100% disabled
* a pension equivalent to 40% of the pension to which the employee would have been entitled, if 100% disabled.
Where the employee dies, each child under 18 years of age is entitled to a monthly pension equal to 20% of the pension which would have been payable to the employee for 100% disablement, up to a maximum of three children.
The maximum pension payable to the spouse and children together is therefore R9 321,00 per month.
All reasonable medical and transport costs arising from the accident are also paid for by the Compensation Fund.
You can apply for compensation from the Compensation Fund at any of these labour centres.
How does this compensation affect a Social Security grant?
Home > Publications > Public Information > T > Government Financial Assistance &gt Road Accident Fund (formerly Multilateral Motor Vehicle Accidents Fund)
Road Accident Fund (formerly Multilateral Motor Vehicle Accidents Fund)
The Road Accident Fund (RAF) was set up to pay compensation in respect of people injured or killed in road accidents through the negligent driving of a motor vehicle in South Africa.
The system was changed so that instead of compulsory insurance, there is now a fund, which gets its money from a levy on the sale of fuel.
People can make a claim for compensation against the RAF if they are injured in a motor vehicle accident as a result of negligent driving.
You must make your application to the RAF within 2 years of the date of the accident in which you sustained your injuries.
You can make the claim yourself by completing Form 1 and submitting all the necessary documents; or you can get an attorney to help with your claim.
The exact amount ("quantum") paid out for a claim against the RAF depends on your medical expenses, your loss of income (past and future), your disablement, and your pain and suffering.
