new opportunities for the minibus taxi industry
the minibus taxi industry has played an important role in keeping the people of cape town on the move .
taxi operators saw an opportunity in the lack of public transport in township areas , and now operate across the city .
even though they did not receive subsidies , minibus taxi operators have provided customised services that other modes have not been able to offer .
today , the industry and the market are changing .
the minibus taxi industry is faced with many pressures , including rising fuel prices , rising labour costs and competition from private cars .
the system entails existing operators joining forces to become shareholders in new operator businesses .
these businesses will provide regular transport services on designated trunk and feeder routes by operating and managing fleets of new vehicles .
there would be a number of advantages , including :
predictable income , because the state will pay the operators per kilometres travelled rather than for the number of passengers carried
dedicated lanes , enabling more runs in the busy peak periods good working conditions for employees , with better pay , training , shorter hours and more career opportunities
a bigger market for public transport as people switch from private cars to the new system
the new system offers existing operators an opportunity to grow their businesses , and participate in a new system that will change our city for the better .
the city of cape town sees those minibus taxi and bus operators whose services will be upgraded by the irt , as preferred partners .
already , operators in the minibus taxi industry have started to grow and diversify their businesses , taking up opportunities in tourism , and learner and student transport .
some have even expanded into related industries , including fuel stations , vehicle dealerships , parts and maintenance .
the minibus taxi industry is maturing , and the entrepreneurs who lead it have shown that they can build and expand their businesses .
as the city of cape town moves ahead with integrated rapid transit , it is looking for a strong partnership with existing operators in planning and developing the system , and ultimately becoming the operators of the new service .
the existing minibus and bus industries must have a voice in shaping the new system .
their expertise will be important in delivering a quality product to the customer .
increased profitability
the new system will deliver increased profitability for operators .
this will be achieved through dedicated lanes , a better fuel economy , bulk buying of new kinds of vehicles and parts , and coordinated marketing and advertising to attract new customers .
a level playing field
the minibus taxi industry has never received operating subsidies from government .
there has long been a sense of unfairness , as some operators are compensated , while others are not .
in the new business model , all operators will be treated equally on a level playing field .
in addition , government will provide capital subsidies to all .
building a partnership with minibus taxi operators
a better way of moving people transforming transport in cape town
the city of cape town is proposing to make far-reaching changes to the citys transport system with the introduction of the integrated rapid transit system .
the city of cape town is engaging with minibus taxi operators to form a partnership to make this a reality .
minibus taxis keep cape town moving
the minibus taxi industry has played an important and historic role in moving the people of cape town .
the industry is the critical link ensuring that ordinary people and low-income communities access jobs and other opportunities throughout the city .
while the minibus taxi industry grew despite the difficulties experienced during the apartheid era , it has continued to contribute to south african society up to the present day , and will no doubt continue to do so .
in addition to the vital transport services the industry provides , it is also a large employer , and many families and communities depend on the industry for their livelihood .
with its important history and contribution to the local economy , the city of cape town wants all existing operators to participate in and benefit from the new system .
