what is hijacking ?
hijacking is the violent theft of a motor vehicle from its owner or driver , and is not classified as a specific crime .
the actual offence is robbery and may include aggravated circumstances .
robbery is defined as the unlawful and intentional violent removal and appropriation of moveable corporeal property belonging to another person , where force or the threat of force is used .
characteristics of hijackings
all hijackings occur unexpectedly .
most hijackings are planned .
provocation is not a prerequisite for a hijacking .
hijackings occur at anytime , day or night .
hijackings can happen anywhere , in urban or rural areas .
any vehicle can be targeted , depending on the demand for it .
common hijacking situations
you could be hijacked ―
while stationary on freeway on or off ramps ;
while loading goods at home or at work ;
while loading passengers ;
while stationary on the side of the road ;
while stationary in a parking area ;
while stationary at stop signs or traffic lights ;
at home , at your gates or in your driveway ; and / or by ambush .
hijacking prevention
when approaching your vehicle , have your car keys ready and lock all doors immediately once you are inside your vehicle .
keep your car and house keys on separate key chains .
make sure you are not being followed .
when approaching a traffic light at night or in secluded areas , reduce speed to avoid having to bring your vehicle to a complete stop .
turn the radio down and observe all approach angles to your vehicle .
if a suspicious person approaches ― and it is safe for you to do so ― drive away .
keep your vehicle in first gear when stationary ― this will allow for a quick getaway in the case of an emergency .
maintain sufficient escape space between vehicles when stationary .
if you cannot afford to have safety film fitted to your vehicles windows , always leave an opening of ± 5 cm from the top .
do not leave valuable items , like handbags , cellphones or laptops on the passenger or back seat ― lock these items in the boot .
kids and car safety seats : put the child in the car safety seat è get into the car è lock all the doors è finish buckling up the child .
when trying to buckle up children and you are bent over into the car , it is impossible to see what is going on around you !
when driving alone , let a family member or friend know the route you are taking and the expected time of arrival at your destination .
